'''Neuvyadaemy Tsvet Icon of the Mother of God''' (Икона Божией Матери «Неувядаемый Цвет») — a revered {{ill|icon|ru|икона}} of the {{ill|Mother of God|ru|Богородица}}, originating from the post-Byzantine artistic tradition. Emerging in the late 17th century, this icon type is believed to have originated in {{ill|Constantinople|ru|Константинополь}} and spread throughout the Orthodox world. The icon’s symbolism is rooted in Byzantine {{ill|Akathists|ru|акафист}}, where the Virgin Mary is likened to unfading and fragrant flowers.
== Iconography == Neuvyadaemy Tsvet icons are highly varied, a hallmark of late-period iconography. A defining feature is the presence of flowers, which may appear in vases, garlands, or blooming staffs. The Virgin and Christ Child are typically depicted in royal garments and crowns, with the Virgin portrayed either half-length or seated on a throne, sometimes unveiled. Flowers such as lilies, representing purity, and roses, symbolizing love, are central elements. In one type, the Mother of God holds the Christ Child and a blooming staff, alluding to the {{ill|Rod of Jesse|ru|Древо Иессеево}}.
The feast of the icon is observed on {{СС|16|April||3}}, though it was once also commemorated on {{СС|13|January||31|December}}.
== Churches in Honor of the Icon == Churches dedicated to the Neuvyadaemy Tsvet Icon include those in {{ill|Rublevo|ru|Рублёво}}, {{ill|Ulyanovsky Forest Park|ru|Посёлок Ульяновского лесопарка}}, and {{ill|Sumarokovo (Ruzsky District)|ru|Сумароково (Рузский городской округ)}}.
== See Also == * {{ill|Madonna with the Carnation|ru|Мадонна с гвоздикой}} * {{ill|Sporitelnitsa Khlebov|ru|Спорительница хлебов}}
