[[File:Neuvyadaemii cvet 18th century icon.jpg|thumb|every|8=en|every|8=en]]The Unfading Flower Icon is a {{ill|Marian apparition|every|8=en|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. It is an important icon in {{ill|Eastern Orthodoxy|lt=Eastern Orthodox Christianity|every|8=en|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. It shows the {{ill|Mary, mother of Jesus|lt=Virgin Mary|every|8=en|qq=draft|qq=draft}} holding {{ill|Christ Child|lt=Baby Jesus|every|8=en|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. She is holding white lilies in her left hand. These lilies represent her virginity and purity.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |title="Unfading Flower" Icon of the Mother of God |url=https://www.oca.org/saints/lives/2021/04/03/100983-unfading-flower-icon-of-the-mother-of-god |access-date=2023-11-10 |website=The Orthodox Church in America | series=The Lives of the Saints | date=2021}}</ref>
== Locations and Veneration == This icon is in several churches in Russia. In Moscow, it is in two churches. One is the Church of the Dormition at Mogil'tsy. This church celebrates it on December 31. The other is the Alexeyev Monastery. There are more icons like this in other places:<ref name=":0" /> * In Kungur, in the Perm Gubernia.<ref name=":0" /> * In the old town of Kadome in the Tambov Province. It is in the Merciful Theotokos women's monastery.<ref name=":0" /> * In the Nativity of the Theotokos church in Voronezh.<ref name=":0" />
== Similar Icon in Budishch == A similar icon is in the village of Budishch. It is in the Church of Saint Nicholas. This icon looks like other old icons in the area. Every year on April 3, people go to Budishch. They go to see this icon and a copy of the Vladimir Icon of the Mother of God. Many believe this icon in Budishch has healing powers. There are stories of sick people getting better after praying in front of it.<ref name=":0" /> {{ill|ru:Неувядаемый_Цвет|every|8=en|qq=draft|qq=draft}} ==Overview==
'''Neuvyadaemy Tsvet Icon of the Mother of God''' (Икона Божией Матери «Неувядаемый Цвет») — a revered {{ill|icon|ru|икона|qq=draft|qq=draft}} of the {{ill|Mother of God|ru|Богородица|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, originating from the post-Byzantine artistic tradition. Emerging in the late 17th century, this icon type is believed to have originated in {{ill|Constantinople|ru|Константинополь|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and spread throughout the Orthodox world. The icon’s symbolism is rooted in Byzantine {{ill|Akathists|ru|акафист|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, where the Virgin Mary is likened to unfading and fragrant flowers.
== Iconography == Neuvyadaemy Tsvet icons are highly varied, a hallmark of late-period iconography. A defining feature is the presence of flowers, which may appear in vases, garlands, or blooming staffs. The Virgin and Christ Child are typically depicted in royal garments and crowns, with the Virgin portrayed either half-length or seated on a throne, sometimes unveiled. Flowers such as lilies, representing purity, and roses, symbolizing love, are central elements. In one type, the Mother of God holds the Christ Child and a blooming staff, alluding to the {{ill|Rod of Jesse|ru|Древо Иессеево|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
The celebration in honor of the icon in the Orthodox Church takes place on [[:en:Julian_Calendar|April <abbr>3</abbr>]] ([[:en:Gregorian_Calendar|16]]) , and previously also took place <abbr>on [[:en:Julian_Calendar|December 31]]</abbr> ([[:en:Gregorian_Calendar|January 13]])<ref>Complete Orthodox Theological Encyclopedic Dictionary. —<abbr>St. Petersburg</abbr>P. P. SoikinPublishing House, 1912. — Vol. II. — P. 1632</ref>
== Churches in Honor of the Icon == Churches dedicated to the Neuvyadaemy Tsvet Icon include those in {{ill|Rublevo|ru|Рублёво|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Ulyanovsky Forest Park|ru|Посёлок Ульяновского лесопарка|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Sumarokovo (Ruzsky District)|ru|Сумароково (Рузский городской округ)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. == See Also == * {{ill|Madonna with the Carnation|ru|Мадонна с гвоздикой|qq=draft|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Sporitelnitsa Khlebov|ru|Спорительница хлебов|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
